sect1.para:
Guatemala, referred to as “eternal spring,” is a country in Central America with an estimated population of over 17 million. Guatemala is inhabited by Mestizo (mixed Amerindian Spanish—in local Spanish called 
               Ladino
            ), K’iche, Kaqchikel, Mam, Q’eqchi, and other Mayan, and indigenous non-Mayan sub-cultural groups. Following the civil war, during the 1960s–1980s, a widespread of mortality, loss of land, community right restrictions, economic instability, and cultural disruption arose, ultimately impacting the structural archetype of everyday life for most Guatemalans. As a result, as many as one million Guatemalan natives fled north toward Mexico and the United States seeking safety and political asylum. The increased migration to the United States created increased difficulties for Guatemalan individuals in regard to cultural differences, language restrictions, and governmental policies. Although much time has passed since the cultural disruption of Guatemala, residing individuals continue to be plagued with “abject” poverty with a majority of the population living below the universal poverty level.

listitem.para:
Modern medicine refers to healthcare provided by educated physicians and nurses, generally in urbanized regions. Ladino folk medicine is provided by Ladino pharmacists, spiritualists, and lay healers (
   curanderos
).
